## Key Concepts

### When to Use What
| Comparison Type | Use |
|----------------|-----|
| Row vs Scalar | Non-Correlated Subquery |
| Row vs Row | Correlated Subquery |
| Row vs Group | Correlated Subquery |
| Group vs Scalar | HAVING + Scalar Subquery |
| Group vs Group | CTE + WHERE |

### Scalar Subquery
- Returns single value
- Runs ONCE
- Use in SELECT, WHERE, HAVING
- Example: Company average, Global max

### Correlated Subquery
- References outer query
- Runs N times (once per row)
- Use for row level comparisons
- Example: Dept average per employee

### EXISTS vs IN
- EXISTS → NULL safe, short circuits ✅
- IN → NULL trap! ⚠️
- NOT EXISTS → always preferred over NOT IN

### ALL vs ANY
- salary > ALL (subquery) → more than maximum
- salary > ANY (subquery) → more than minimum

### Important Rules
1. Subquery in WHERE/SELECT → single column only!
2. Subquery in FROM → multiple columns okay, alias required!
3. Correlated → always use table aliases (e1, e2)
4. PARTITION BY → only for group wise ranking
5. No PARTITION BY → for overall ranking

## Important Notes

### Scalar vs Correlated vs CTE Together
```sql
-- Real world: All three used together
WITH dept_avg AS (          -- CTE (Group level)
  SELECT dept, AVG(salary) AS dept_average
  FROM employees
  GROUP BY dept
)
SELECT
  name,
  salary,
  (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees) AS company_avg,  -- Scalar
  da.dept_average                                        -- CTE value
FROM employees e
JOIN dept_avg da ON e.dept = da.dept
WHERE salary > (                                         -- Correlated
  SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees e2
  WHERE e2.dept = e.dept
);
```

